s we are already In the campaii\nand us we can reach so l'ew people with e\nvoices, 1 am glad to pay for the necessary spa\nin the daily papers to say a little bit of t\nmuch we might say about what we hope\n1 accomplish.\nAll of us who are whole-heartedly supporti\ntiie Thrift movement believe it is not only hel\nful to business but absolutely necessary f\nj business.\n'i As a portion of Thrift Week is already go\nwe cannot get together and harmonize our d:\nI ferences of opinion; so the only thing left for\nj to do Is to use space in the daily papers\npresent our views and invite th<mo who disse\nto present their views frankly and in a li\nmanner.\n.1 \\e.. mm thai Thrift I tavMtMM U\nall timer* helpful to business arid that it is p>\ntlcularly nee<led Just now. Our non-symt\nthlisers. we understand, think Thrift and I\nvestment is generally a good thliiK, but tti\njust now it will accentuate 'be so-called Ituye\nStrike.\nSome merchants se? m to tliltik that an Ami\nlean Federation of Retail Buyers has sprung\nover niaht which In strength and dctermir\ntinn is euual to the American Federation\nLabor, end that th> first thing the new Feder\ntion did was to declare u Buyers Strike.\nv There is no mere of a \"Buyers Strike\" a mo\nl the retail buyers than there Is a Buyers Stri\non the part of the retail merchants theme'-).\nDon't vou think that figures would sb ,w tt\nthe public Is buying more from the i^ii m<\nchant than the retail merchant Is .iu;.ing fr(\nthe Jobber and the manufacturer? How ma\nj; retail merchants do von think are willing\ntake the m> ney theli retail 11stomer pays th?\nand pass the ptoper share of it right along\nthe jobber and to the factory for more goods'\nHew many merchants do vpu think ore\nready carrying less than normal stocks?-?a\nhow many do you think of those who\ncarrying normal or abnormal stocks would i\nsjst ttic temptation to reduce their stocks 1\nbelow normal if they could create enough i\ntail buying to enable them to do so?\nNow. we have all seen some wonderfu\nclever advertisements telling why the j>eo\nI .'.1 1 ti ii i-, It i r., 1 i lilti r-i. llv I hm>A i v\nI I merchant who in not in sympathy with the\ntionul Thrift Drive will get these odvertli\nnient* and rend th?in over and make up\nmind how much of the advice given to the i\ntall buyer he will accept for himself and h\nmurh of thl* advice he thinks his fellow m<\nchant will accept.\nj Let me remind you that our present troub\nwere brought on largely by wild and i xtrai\n*ant buying on the part of the public. Itet\nmerchants were encouraged to place abnorma\nIn lite orders to Insure against depletion\nstocks and rely on their bmks to carry the\nThis, with the load the hanks were nlren\n-urrylng. brought a strain on our hanking sj\n'-m which curried It to its full clastic IIit\n1 i Money thereafter had to he rationed T\nVu'.iltc In some cases bought until they h\n__ THE\nESEMEHT f ADVERTISEMENT.\nHPJFT vs. SF\nwhatever Thrift Movement by thos?\nike to you lieve it is harmful to bus\n>r at arw at this time. 1\niver form locating Thrift are so coi\ni 'o geltirg almo t universal pi\nread this port that they desire to\ninst doing widest publicity to everyt\nspecially can be said for and again\nsets under They believe every \"kr\nis given thoughtful people, will pr\n1 that any a \"boost.\"\nsend you They desire to have the\njquired to published as a matter o\nWhile these letters deal\nde Thrift with the question of whetl\nd at this or Spending is best for th\nuppo~ters. under present conditions,\n1 to this incidently touch upon tl\n:S MESSAGE\ners* Strike\nSpending\ncrs published in this paper\nin 78, 1921.\nr- b. come overstocked and the retail merchants\nIt. in oihi eases bought until they had liecome\no.\" overstoi ked.\nit\nf \"rb ret 1 customer does not buy in greater\n1- volume, lirst, because the man out of employee\nment is not apt to have the money or credit\ne- with which to buy and the man who is still\nemployed sees widespread unemployment and\nwonders how secure his employment is; second,\nbecause a large portion of the public think we\nar going to have still lower prices.\nNow. some of the retail merchants do not buy,\nfirst, because they fear that the business depression\nhas become so widespread that the future\npurchasing power of the American people has\nbeen seriously crippled; second, because they\nfear stiii lower prices; and, third, because they\nare having difficulty in raising the money necessary\nto pay their obligations when they come\ndue.\nThere Is nothing in the National Thrift movement\nwhich opposes judicious or conservative\nbuying. There is no reason why the merchant\nshould not strive to stimulate buying, and there\nis no reason why he should not tell his customer\nthat it is his belief that prices have\nreached the bottom, if he really believes it\nhimself.\nBut, Mr. Merchant, let's be fair again. We\nknow prices have been- abnormally high. We\nall hoped they would come back to normal in a\ngradual and orderly manner?that they would\nevolute, not revolute; but when we reached the\nlimit of our hanking credit, and the bankers had\nto call a halt, then, in many cases, factories,\nJobbers and retailers had to so'l some of their\ngoods for whatever they would bring?and here\nand there some commodities had to be sold at\nr~ loss than the pre-war cost of production,\nsn\nur Now, what do you think is the greatest threat\nee >f further demoralization of prices? I think the\nhe greatest threat is to have further forced ,-alos.\nto lxm't lots'et that many, and, in fact, most of\nthese forced sales were not due to lack of capital,\nhut due to la k of cash. Don't forget,\n11 either, that there are still many factories, jobP\"\nhers and retailers who are still under a great\nor strain, and although they have an abundance\nof capital yet they are finding it difficult to tind\nthe cash to meet their obligations.\nThose of us who are supporting th s National\nus Thrift movement believe that money applied to\nto these strained situations will do more to help the\nnt mercantile situation than a like amount of money\nke applied to indiscriminate buying Illustrating\nperhaps by exaggeration, we feel that If the man\nwho nus an uppet te to smoke a one dollar mi 'lt\nported cigar would content himself with a ten\n,r\" cent domestic cigar, and would say Ho the sound\n,a* merchant who is under a strain: \"Here is ninety\nn* cents that I will loan you to help prevent vou\nia^ from lx lnv compelled to make p. forced Hale of\nr>l your goods,\" wo think that this would aid the\nntirc business and mercantile situation more\nthan If he had bought and smoked the one dollar\ncigar. Now, we know that ninety eenta would\n1 not help very much, and we know that this\nman, and the man like him. cannot deal direct\nw th the merchant; but all of these people can\na~ deposit in some bank, which. In turn, will use It\nto help out these particularly strained business\nn,r situations and prevent forced selling,\nke\n(1(t I know a great many of the men who are\n1Jit working wholeheartedly l>ehlnd th National\nThrift moverm nt Many of them are merchants\n_ ihemselv-s. None of them wants to interfere\njm\ntiV with the business of our merchants but to be\nhelpful to them- If we are wrong you can tell\n,m !he people why in the papers to-morrow.\n-The foregoing letter Is but little of what can\nbe said in favor of support of the Nat onal Thrift\nill- movement, but if whnt has already been said\nnd sounds reasonable thi n take a chance and get\nire l\"h!nd the National ThrP't Drive with your\nwhop- heart in it. Give the publ e ihe assurance\n\\-ir thnt the business rnen of the country are fully\nrP. cognisant of the sltuat on, that they arc not fearful\naUiut It and will not themselves \"hunt cover\"\nand thnt they m-Tin to correct the situation n.<\nily rapidly as circumstances will permit, and you\npi* will chanjre the mind of the retail buyer over\ntry nljrhf\ni M\n\"onservatlve huyinjr will again Mart up ami\n(1>( the buyer will pay what price lie must whether\nhe thinks It in the bottom prim or not, and more\n(iW will bo accomplished than by any attempt to\nr| break up the so-called buyer's strike.\nThursday, If 1 am not called upon to make\nfurther r< ply alora this line. I will tell you som<?\nof the reasons why I am a derided optimist on\nru\" the business outlook provided the employers will\nH\" yet behind n Thrift and Investment Movement\nand try to show why wise Investing !n truth\nwise spending and will help more than the ex*\nfn penditure whlrh buys something which la con<?'\nHutnfd\nFaithfully yours,\nHKMHY L. I>' dlKllTV,\nad (10 Wall St.. New York\nII\nNEW YORK HERALD,\nadvebtisement.\nENDING\nwho be- Question, the Ba\nine-3s and the Unemploym\nm l\ninose aa- may prove won\nifident of keenly intereste\nublic sup- and to student's\ngive the omy. If in doub\nhing that is worth reading\nist Thrift, it out and lay it\njock,\" to your leisure if t\nove to be one of further\nwill undoubted!)\n;se letters Thrift, for furthe\nif record. is going on now\nprimarily upon a still m\ntier Thrift scale.\ne country v\ni Yours\nthey also\ntie Labor HEI\nThis letter was\npublicity colum\nWednesday, J a,\nNATIi )NA L I' 1?SI'BRITV\nBURBA\nINCOKfl 'ORATED\nExecutive Offices. Masonic Bldg..\nNew York Cm'.\nJanuary 19, 1921\nMr. Henry L. Dohep.ty\nfiO Wall Street,\nNew York City.\nDear Sir:\nIt is not singular in these unsettled\nbusiness conditions that both\nthe \"thrift\" campaign, of which you\nare an eminent exponent and\nspokesman, and the \"buy now\"\nmovement, conducted by the National\nProsperity Bureau, should\narouse widespread Interest. While\nthere is much that is common\nground in these efforts, thp impression\npersists in many quarters that\nI.IICII fJUI 1-njr.r-o n. t\nthat your own position in many respects\nis self-contradictory.\nWe frankly agree with your\nviews that economy and thrift, under\nnormal conditions, can and will\ndo much good; with your contention\nthat the retailer in many instances\nis himself engaged in a\nbuyers' strike, and with your premise\nthat economic conditions have\nbeen in a large measure the result\nof extravagnnt buying. Likewise,\nwe agree with your conclusions\nthat many merchants are disinclined\nnow to replenish their stores\nbecause of your stated apprehensions.\nTo be equa'ly frank, we find our-\nselves not entirely in accord with\nyour exnlanntions of the causes of\nthese conditions and with your proposed\nremedies.\nThe accepted purpose of the\n\"thrift\" campaign projected and\ncarried on at this time, is to induce\nthe average man to get along with\nas little as he possibly can and to\ntake the balance of his earnings\n1 <n U Kavinsrs Hank\nor In an Insurance Company to invest\nIt, or, himself, to invest It in\nrecommended investment securities,\nthus enabling those institutions to\nextend credit to clients.\nWhat these clients, whether they\nbe railroads, manufacturing1 industries\nor trading concerns, will do\nwith mere currency and without an\noutlet for their commodities, is\nrather obscure to us. All the money\nin the world, if there is no demand\nfor and consumption of the commodities\nwhich labor is engaged in\nproducing will not. we fear, relieve\nthe demoralized situation.\nObviously, then, the thrift program\ncannot help us out of the situation.\nThe root of the entire evil, be the\ncause of it what it may, is the buyers'\nstrike, and the only remedy is\na revival of a public interest In\npurchasing.\nWhether the public is or is not\njustified in its present apathy, is\nanother question. some nay mm.\nthe public strike is Justified because\nthe prices of commodities have not\nappreciably declined. On the other\nhand, the position is tnken that the\nbuyers' strike is not Justified becnuxe\nthe price of lai>or has not\nequally appreciably declined.\nThe public cannot on the one\nhand insist on a maintenance of Its\npresent wage-paming scale, and on\nthe other hand Justify Its refusal\nto purchase Its needs. In any event,\nto look for pre-war prices as .1\ncriterion for prices to-day, is manifestly\nunsound, not only because\nof the reason Just stated, but because\nof the additional burden Imposed\nupon all produetlnn hy Iho\ntremendous war loans now being\ncarried by business as a part of its\ngeneral overhead.\n4\nsmiIiJIH li.Jto ii.il., ii >iiJ 11 r11 \"uiV111 j\nSUNDAY, JANUARY 2;\nADVERTISEMENT.\n\nnking Situation and\nent Problem. They\n;h reading to those\nd in these subjects\nof Political Econ\n-u;\nl wneuier mis page\nI I suggest you tear\naside to be read at\nhe subject becomes\ncontroversy. Y ou\ny hear much about\n:r organization work\nto carry it forward\nore comprehensive\ncordially,\nMRY L. DOHERTY\nreleased to the\nins of the press,\nnuary 19,1921.\nWe are not justifying' high prices.\nOn the contrary, we consider it the\nfunction of all serious tr.en to help\nmake prices more attractive to the\nconsumer in order to stimulate his\npurchasing activity.\nTo our way of thinking.the only\n-eal test of fair value is the price\ntf any commodity when it reaches\nhe point at which it beeomes attractive\nenough for the public to\npurchase it. The ability and willingness\nof the; public to buy, and\nthe tendency of business men to enter\nand compete in new fields which\npromise large profits, Is a sufficient\ngauge, and at the same time safety\nvalve, for determining fuir prices at\nany particular time.\nIt. is because of this interpretation\nas to what constitutes a fair\nprice of commodities that we cnnnot\nagree with your appraisal of\ntlie importance which forced sales\nplay in the present demoralization of\nprices. Admittedly, the thrift campaign\nis calculated to prevent such\nforced sales. How ready are these\nfinancial institutions to prevent,\nsuch forced sales lnlo which financially\nembarrassed clients are\ndriven? Who will answer this question\non behalf of the banks? Assuming\nthat the banks or other\nfinancial institutions would be rash\nenough to loan money to clients in\nsuch a predicament, how is this\nclient?ra manufacturer or dealer or\njobber?in a better position to accelerate\nmovement of his merchandise?\nTo us the danger of demoralization\nin prices is merely one of the\neffects of the greater cause which\nlies in the buyers' refusal to buy.\nand. concurrently, in the weakening\npower of the consumer to buy.\nThe buying power of the American\npeople was at its very highest\nsoma months ago. not only because\nall American Industry was\nthen engaged and received the\nhighest remuneration for its labor,\nbut because labor, in spite of its\nspending orgy, had managed to accumulate\nmoney. The buying power\nof the American people has remained\nsubstantially unimpaired,\nexcept in spots where unemployment\nand reduction in wages exist, both\nof which were directly the result of\nthe nublic's buvinc slrlke. Logical\nly, business conditions will become\nmore aggravated by any increase of\nunemployment or further reduced\nwaxes; they will Improve as Industry\nresumes its normal functions,\nwhich depend upon the free circulation\nof the dollar.\nThese propositions are basic and\ncannot be waved aside by the optimistic\nprophesies that all that the\n\"public requires is assurance that\nthe business men are cognizant of\nthe situation\"; that they are not\nfearful about It and will not themselves\n\"hunt rover.\" Granted thnt\nthe business men realize the situation,\nand granted that they are not\nfearful about It, how are you going\nto dispense over night with the\nmenace of three million unemployed,\nwith the list growing, and\nwith its power to participate in the\nmarket weakening? By what\nmiracle do you believe the mind of\nthe retail buyer will he changed\nover night In the mere belief that\nconditions will he corrected by\nbusiness men \"cognizant of the\nsituation and not fearful about It''?\nWe do not believe the panacea\nwhich you propose will reopen mills\nand replace three million men back\non to their Johs. That we realize\nto he only capable of accomplish\nn.mt within h rea?on?ble time by\nnrt lnt?n?tro campaign to cdicato\nthe public to the urgency of keeping\nup tho normal buying of lta\nneed* and )?y teaching manufacturers,\ntraders an 1 retailers tho neces;\nfty for attracting the public into\nthe market nlace.\nYours very truly,\nnational rttnapbrirr byrkac. inc.,\nMv Jamkh Rosthai Director.\nt\n_\n3, 1921.\n1 ADVEEnSEMEN'r AD1\nThis le'ter is in re\nwhich appt\nJanuary 20th, 1921.\nNational Prosperity Bureatt,\nMasonic Building,\nNew York City.\nGentlemen:\nI received your letter of the 10th ut 3:45 P. M.\nwhile presiding over n regular monthly meeting\nof the Board of Directors of Cities Service Company,\nand owing to this and to several other\nrapidly succeeding engagements until quite late\nin the ereniuir I was unable to reply until to-day.\nFirst let me express my appreciation of the\ntone of your letter. While I cannot agree with\nyour position, nevertheless I Rive you credit for\nbeing as sincere In your views as 1 know I am\nin mine.\nIf the \"impression persists that your\nown (my) position is self-contradictory\" I want\nto correct it, If possible. I always try to think\nstraight and then try to speak or write my\nthoughts plainly. If I am wrong In any way I\nwill he glad to he set right, and If I have advocated\na wrong policy I will without hesitancy\npublicly endeavor to make amends. These are\ntimes when our difficulties entitle the public to\nearnest discussion to harmonize differences of\nopinion rather than argue for the sake of Justifying\na selfish position.\nI have carefully read your letter with an earnesf\nendeavor to preserve an open inlnd, and it\nis only fair to you to say that it has not changed\nmy opinion in the least.\nYou admit in the second paragraph of your\nletter that the present \"economic conditions have\nbeen in a large measure the result of extravagant\nbuying.\" Now. it you had a patient who was suffering\nfrom over eating, you would not resort to\nforced-feeding when his stomach turned against\nfood simply because he had speeded up his favorite\nrestaurant to a certain volume of business\nand that therefore this volume of business had\nto lie maintained. Or. if you had n patient suffering\nfrom over-drinking, you would not urge\nhim to drink more .lost because his wine merchant\nhad become over-stocked, even though this\nstock had been contracted for based upon his\nformer rote of patronage.\nYou say, \"The root of the entire evil,*\nIs the buyers' strike.'' Surely you do\nnot mean that the buyers' strike is what tins produced\nour present situation. It is far from a\n\"root.\" It is a natural reaction from the \"spending\norgy\" which prevailed, and which you speak\nabout in the thirteenth paragraph of your letter.\nBefore the \"spending orgy\" had spent itself we\nhad reached the point in our financial strain\nwhich In the Judgment of our bankers required\nthem to call a halt and to Place the business\nworld on rationed loans.\nI cannot accept, and do not necessarily dispute,\nthe statement you made In the fourth paragraph\nof your letter. My idea of Thrift is. Work and\nEarn?Don't Waste. Save part of what you enrn\nand deposit or invest it where It is safe and\nwhere It will do you the most good.\nThere are hundreds of men who have abundant\ncapital who are applicants for the loan of cash\nfrom their banks, but the banks are unable to\nloan them as freely as they need the money or as\nKonba ivAiili! lilro tn rl#* >*li< ilmco hntllffi\nand especially the commercial hunks, can be de\npointed upon to lonn tills money wherever It Is\nsafe and where It Is most needed rather than to\nlonn It purely for their own selfish interest. Inability\nof many manufacturing concerns to raise\ncash by the pledge of capital Is what has caused\nthe vast army of unemployed. Give them a\nchance to get onsh for the pledge of capitnl and\nthey will resume operations, giving employment\nto the unemployed, thus reestablishing the purchasing\npower of the public and enabling themselves\nto convert capitnl Into cash, with which\nto repay these loans.\nPeople will buy if they have money to buy\nwith?end the world problem has never been to\nstimulate the need and desire for consumption,\nhut to produce In sufficient abundance what Is\nneeded for consumption. What brought us to\nour present situation was the tendency to consume\nuntil we had en ten our seed corn. So I\ncannot concur in your statement that \"Obviously\nthen the thrift program cannot help us out of the\nsituation.\"\nWe who are advocating Thrift as a cure for\nour troubles cannot undertake to have cither\nlabor or the hanks conduct themselves *to your\nliking, but we will gladly Join with you to Induce\nthe hanks or labor to do that which Is best\nfor our country as a whole, believing In this\nv.ill prosper more wilh n thoroughly wound oon*111Ion\nof the country throughout than by having\nroute selfish advantage over others through what\nmay prove a period of great business depression.\nYon refer to Labor In n way which questions\nwhether Its ntt'tude la cofjstrect'vo In the present\nsituation, and I thlnfc you may well do so. Hut\ndo not forget that we are apt to see the faults of\nothers more readily than we see their virtues.,\n\n(TERTISEMENT. I ADVERTISEMENT.\nsponse to the letter 3\n\\ars to the left, j\nTlie worlds progress hns largely been brought\nabout by the creation and introduction of labor- p\nsaving machinery. We cannot deny that the Intro-\nductlon of every ejtoch-inaklng piece of labor-sav-\ning muchlnery seriously Inconvenienced, and somewhat\npunished large groups of wage-earners, and S\nyet we know that Labor could never have enjoyed c\nits present comfort of living and short labor hours\nthat are now possible if it had not been for the\nintroduction of this labor-saving machinery. Every i\nother country has been compelled to fight the false\ntut plausible doctrines of economy that have been\nadvanced to prevent the Introduction of labor- 4\nsaving machinery to a greater extent than have\nwe. Our American Labor lias boon vastly more 3\nconstructive than many men give them credit for.\nAnd while not defending Organized Labor. I *9\ncould cite other examples of the virtue of Ameri- 'jj|\ncan Labor If called upon to do so. I mention\nthis one example, and state that the position of\nthe merchants who oppose; the Thrift and Invest-\nment Movement is based on equally false eco-\nnomic premises, and, while highly plausible, is*\nstill not so plausible or justifiable as the opposition\nof Labor to the Introduction of labor-saving\nmachinery.\nSurely the merchants, unconsciously prompted\nby selfish interests, do not want to fall into the\nerror of supporting a false economic doctrine\nthat lacks even the plausibility or justification\nof things which even Organized Labor has not\nfallen error to. Here is a statement and I Jj\ndon't see how it can be successfully contradicted\nby any amount of argument, viz.: The more we\ncreate and the less we consume, the greater will\nhe our accumulation of wealth. All the labor for\nmany generations to come can find abundant em- v\nploy ment along the lines which create permanent\nproperty In the true sense, and- the need and de-\nsire for consumption does not have to be stimu\nla ted to provide employment.\nI can neither concur in, nor xlo I here take\nexception, to the definition of a \"fair price\" as\ngiven in the tenth paragraph of your letter. My\nown way of stating the natural laws which fix\nprices is by saying,?Except under emergency i'1\nconditions natural laws fix as a minimum price 1\nthe cost of production when it reaches the con- -J\nsiimcr in final form, and its maximum price is its tj\nvalue to the consumer regardless of Its price of\nproduction but. generally speaking, a \"fair price\" j\nis that which properly, hut not unwnrrantedly,\nrewards those who produce and distribute and i\ngives sufficient reward to attract both capital ~j\nand labor. j\nForced sales, however, entirely disregard natu- J\nral laws ns to cost of production, and moral laws .I\nas to fair prices and forced purchases do likewise 3\nin the opposite direction. The man without water, a\nor sufficient water, stranded on the desert will J\npay any price he may have to for water?and a] J\nthat brings me to this point, viz.: that T fear that v'j 1\nmany of our retail merchants failed to console N\nthemselves with another very natural application 1\nof natural laws. When prices were ascending i i\nthey found themselves able to sell their goods at w\nmore than a fair margin above their cost, and t\nyet they failed to set aside a contingent fund on j\ntheir hooks, or a contingent thought in their J\nminds, that when prices would again descend to\nnormal they would find themselves victims of the ,i\nreaction of an economic law and compelled to v\naccept some losses, just its they had taken their\nprofits.\nNow, just to save you the trouble of calling\nmy attention to the fact that the Treasury's ruling*:\ndid not adequately provide for this otfsetling\nof profits against inevitable losses, I will admit it.\nOn the other hand, those of us who advocate\nThrift do not attempt to defend the present\nRevenue Law or the Treasury's rulings?nnd we '1\nthink the law was a most unthrifty one. '.,1\nReferring to your quotation of my statements\nin tlie fourteenth paragraph of your letter, T\nwish to say that I had no intention of setting up\nn mere figment in the minds of tiie people that\nwas without substance. I stand ready to do my\nshare toward any movement which will arrest\nfurther demoralization?hut it would be too long\na matter to suggest and discuss plans here by\nletter. The financial trade conditions have been\nturned many times by cooperation and dotermination,\nbut I am unable at this moment to refer ft]\nto any concrete example in the mercantile trades; ;j\nhut any of the frequent examples in the financial jn\nworld are equally applicable in the mercantile t\nworld. Perhaps the moat*outstanding one in the r'\nfinancial world, and from which you might borrow\nan example, was tlie way flte Baring Brothers j<Crisis\nwas met and solved in 1NOO by the London\nbanking houses, led by officials of the Bank of c\nKnglnnd. 1 regret that I cannot, at this moment\ncite you to some book which will detail this to i,\nyou, hut will endeavor to make a search of my\nlibrary this evening and tell you definitely where\nyou can road up about It.\nNow, f hope 1 have convinced you that we do\nnot want to nocrnr rms panenr wnn is sunering i\nfrom over-eating by further forced-feeding, fie 1\nwill soon hu.v and'ent more if you do not resort\nto forced-feeding while be Is 111. I also hof?c this\nletter will convert yon to the Thrift Plan. If It\ndoes, get In quick and with your whole heart, for\nIt means, In my opinion, the speediest cure for\nour ailments. However, whether I have or not,\nlet's not he thin-skinned, and let's try and set an U\nexample whereby all of the differences of opinion H\nregarding our Mg national questions can be *?j\ntied by earnest discussion rntlier than by long H\ncontroversies, whether It Is n financial, nn Indus- jl\ntrial, a mercantile or a labor problem. 1\nYom-s oortllally, I\ni Signed IIKXIIY T.. r>OlIE!lTY. I","height":"24282","width":"19566"}}
